There are no syntax errors in the code, but there are a few mistakes related to the logic and structure of the code:

1. The `reset()` function is called outside of any event listener or function, meaning it will be called as soon as the page loads, before the user has a chance to interact with the checkboxes and dropdown menu. This could be confusing for the user and not provide the desired functionality.

2. The `reset()` function only resets the checkboxes for "arroz" and "batatas", but not the dropdown menu for the "prato" option. This means that if the user selects a prato, then resets the page, the dropdown menu will still show the previously selected option. 

3. The `pedido()` function only sets the `um.src` value for specific combinations of options, meaning that if the user selects a prato but does not select any checkboxes, the image will remain unchanged, rather than resetting to the default image.

4. There are a lot of repeated lines of code for loading images. This could be easily streamlined and made more efficient with a loop or function.

Possible solutions to these issues:

1. Move the `reset()` function call to the "Reset" button's `onclick` event, so it is only called when the user wants to reset the form.

2. Add a line to the `reset()` function that sets the dropdown menu back to the default option: `document.getElementById("prato").selectedIndex = 0;`

3. Add an `else` statement to the end of the `pedido()` function that sets `um` to the default image if no specific options are selected: 

```
if (tipodeprato == "") {
  um.src = img0.src;
} else if (/* other conditions */) {
  // set um.src accordingly
} else {
  um.src = img0.src;
}
```

4. Use a loop to load the images more efficiently:

```
var imgNames = ["restaurante", "carne", "carnea", "carneb", ...]; // add all image names in order

var imgArray = [];
for (var i = 0; i < imgNames.length; i++) {
  var img = new Image();
  img.src = imgNames[i] + ".jpg";
  imgArray.push(img);
}
```

This will create an array of `Image` objects and load the images in the order specified in `imgNames` array. This makes the code shorter and more modular.

