To capture the first arg in one variable and the remaining args in a list, you can use Perl's shift function. Here's an example:

```
sub my_sub {
    my $first_arg = shift;
    my @remaining_args = map { s/\$/\\\$/g; $_ } @_;
    # do something with $first_arg and @remaining_args
}
```

In this example, we first use `shift` to remove the first element of `@_`, which is then assigned to `$first_arg`. We then use `map` to iterate over the remaining elements in `@_`, applying a substitution that adds a backslash before every `$`. This is done to escape any variables that may be in the arguments, so that they are treated literally.

The resulting array `@remaining_args` contains all the remaining arguments, with any variables escaped. You can then use this array to do whatever processing you need to do.

